the new sesquipedalian blog archive rickford in guyana the new sesquipedalian the stanford linguistics newsletter department events calendar archive subscribe rickford in guyana john rickford was in guyana last week the country of his birth and k 12 education he gave two talks the first entitled if yuh see people appreciating the systematicity and expressiveness of creolese guyanese english creole and the second was a faculty development seminar on research and publication given at the university of guyana berbice campus find out more at this guyana times article and read the abstract from the first talk below if yuh see people appreciating the systematicity and expressive power of creolese it is common to dismiss creolese and other pidgins creoles and non standard vernaculars as unsystematic language varieties which sharply limit the expressive potential and social mobility of their speakers the social mobility issue is open to discussion since it varies by place and time and is subject to the larger social and political context in new guinea for instance pidgin english is used in parliament and in haiti creole is recognized as a national language and used in many schools but on the issue of systematicity and expressive ness there can be no doubt for at least half a century it has been clear that creoles are systematic rule governed varieties with tremendous expressive power in this talk drawing on my own research and that of other linguists engaged in the scientific study of language i will attempt to reveal the ruliness and expressive potential of creolese drawing on examples from its vocabulary pronunciation grammar and narrative structure as deployed by guyanese from many different walks of life including cane cutters and farmers weeding gang and market women teachers and civil servants sesquipedalian issue 2012 03 02 faculty eckert like quoted in the times much vilainy in today's p&p workshop search for in this issue python pyphon in p&p meeting johnston talk 